 > with you that it's not the most accepted way to solve this
 > particular problem, but we have little risk here. If you want to
 > talk about risk, it seems mighty easy with your implementation for
 > the caller to forget to initialize the required properties for the
 > DmaapConsumer and DmaapPublisher. If only there was a way to
 > guarantee that our objects completed all their required
 > initialization before being used....wait a minute.

I don't understand why you want to create instance of abstract class. The point I'm trying to make is: don't call non-static methods in constructor. Simple example can be:

public abstract AbstractClass {
    public AbstractClass() {
        System.out.println(getName());
    }
    public abstract String getName();
}

public Impl extends AbstractClass {
    String name;

    public Impl(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

In this example creating new object of Impl causes to printing null to console instead of name, which clearly isn't wanted behaviour.

